body:
GCT Views with zero width components is also busted similarly to #3458.

Consider:

```scala
circuit ZeroWidth : %[[
  {
    "class": "sifive.enterprise.grandcentral.GrandCentralView$SerializedViewAnnotation",
    "name": "MyView",
    "companion": "~ZeroWidth|MyView_companion",
    "parent": "~ZeroWidth|ZeroWidth",
    "view": {
      "class": "sifive.enterprise.grandcentral.AugmentedBundleType",
      "defName": "MyInterface",
      "elements": [
        {
          "name": "ground",
          "description": "a ground type port",
          "tpe": {
            "class": "sifive.enterprise.grandcentral.AugmentedGroundType",
            "refBetter": "~ZeroWidth|ZeroWidth>w",
            "ref": {
              "circuit": "ZeroWidth",
              "module": "ZeroWidth",
              "path": [],
              "ref": "w",
              "component": []
            },
            "tpe": {
              "class": "sifive.enterprise.grandcentral.GrandCentralView$UnknownGroundType$"
            }
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  }
]]
  module MyView_companion :

  module ZeroWidth :

    wire w : UInt<0>
    w is invalid
    inst MyView_companion of MyView_companion
```

Running this through Grand Central will currently not do the right thing. This should not emit an XMR and do something with the zero-width port. Currently ExportVerilog will generate a 1-bit logic with an inline comment. (This should probably be changed, but is different from this issue as we still don't want the XMR.)
